          Week, April 15, 1996. </p>
		  <p class="auto-style20">&nbsp;<o:p> </o:p>
        <div style="mso-element:endnote" id="edn2">
            <p class="auto-style8">
          <a style="mso-endnote-id:edn2" href="#_ednref2" name="_edn2" title>
			<span style="mso-special-character: footnote; mso-fareast-font-family: Times New Roman; mso-ansi-language: DE; mso-fareast-language: DE; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA" class="auto-style2">[ii]</span></a><font face="Times New Roman"><span style="mso-fareast-font-family:
&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;mso-ansi-language:DE;mso-fareast-language:DE;mso-bidi-language:
AR-SA" class="auto-style2"><span class="auto-style12">Allmendinger, J. &amp; Hackman, J.R., &quot;The More, the Better?,&quot;
          unpublished working paper<span style="mso-bidi-font-style:normal"> 
			</span></span><span style="mso-spacerun: yes" class="auto-style12">&nbsp;</span><span class="auto-style12">(Harvard
          Business School, January 1994) pg. 11.</span><span style="mso-spacerun: yes" class="auto-style12">&nbsp;
          </span><span class="auto-style12">See also: &quot;The More, the Better?</span><span style="mso-spacerun: yes" class="auto-style12">&nbsp;
